Expressions, statements, and operators.

Start with a distinction that runs through Java's whole grammar. An expression produces a value: one plus two is an expression, calling a method that returns something is an expression, and so is the ternary, condition question-mark a colon b. A statement, by contrast, performs an action and produces no value: a variable declaration, an if block, a while loop. This is the opposite of Scala, where if and while are themselves expressions. In Java they are statements, so they cannot sit on the right-hand side of an assignment. The switch expression, added in Java fourteen, is the one place Java gave control flow a real expression form.

Java's operators will look familiar from C, Python, and JavaScript, but a few behave in Java-specific ways. Integer division truncates, so seven divided by two is three, not three point five. For comparison, double equals on primitives compares their values, but double equals on reference types compares the references themselves, so to compare the contents of two objects you use the dot equals method. And there is a Java-specific unsigned right shift, written as three greater-than signs.

That equality point is the classic beginner trap, so burn it in. Two separate string objects with the same text are not double-equals equal, because they are different objects, but they are dot-equals equal, because their contents match. On reference types, double equals compares identity and dot equals compares content. The only safe use of double equals on a reference is checking whether it is null.
